tweet: Did you know that formerly incarcerated New Jersey citizens can register to vote while on parole or probation? name: New Jersey Secretary of State Tahesha Way
tweet: @_AndrewFriedman It depends on how quickly your Board of Elections is able to process the ballots as they are picked up on a daily basis. Some voters have reported seeing their ballot show as "received" within a few days, but it may take a bit longer.

name: New Jersey Secretary of State Tahesha Way
tweet: October 13 is the last day to register to vote in New Jersey in time to participate in this election. You've got 1 week left to become a New Jersey voter if you aren't already. Not sure if you're registered? Check the "Am I Registered?" tool first.  https://t.co/erBmfdvstE

name: New Jersey Secretary of State Tahesha Way
tweet: @heyitskj_ it is possible there has just been a slight mail delay. Your county clerk has until today to place your ballot in the mail. If it hasn't arrived in a few more days, reach out to the clerk's office and they will assist you in making sure you can cast a ballot.

name: New Jersey Secretary of State Tahesha Way
tweet: @scottsix @NJGov Ballots are collected from the dropboxes on a daily basis and some voters have reported seeing their account update with the ballot received notation within a day or two.

name: New Jersey Secretary of State Tahesha Way
tweet: @scottsix @NJGov Hi Scott, your ballot will be marked "received" when the County Board of Elections has retrieved and processed your ballot from the dropbox. Your ballot would be marked as "accepted" when it has been counted.
